      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm studying for my accounting exam and I'm stuck on depreciation. Can you explain the formula for straight-line depreciation and give me an example? Let's say a company buys a piece of heavy machinery for $50,000, it has a salvage value of $5,000, and a useful life of 5 years. How would you calculate that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The straight-line depreciation formula calculates the annual expense by subtracting the asset's salvage value from its cost and dividing the result by its useful life in years. For your machinery costing $50,000 with a $5,000 salvage value over 5 years, you first determine the depreciable base of $45,000 ($50,000 - $5,000). Dividing this base by 5 years results in an annual depreciation expense of $9,000. This means the company records a $9,000 depreciation charge on its books every year until the asset reaches its salvage value.",
